Thus, since the last non-European Commission in the area of regulation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation is likely to occur - the SMS sent abroad will be for some customers of Czech mobile operators less expensive than the country.
How is it possible for prices in Czechia to remain so high in comparison with Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that would really want to get into the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, since we have even three mobile networks and a penetration that goes beyond 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this regard, Pavel Dvorák, President of the Czech Telecommunications Council (ČTÜ), who has stated several times that there was no room for another operator in Chequie, has been working with operators.
It is likely true that a classic operator with his own network does not appear to have much more chance (and he would now find it difficult to find the frequencies).
But there is another possibility - a virtual operator.
It is just the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that has led to a considerable decline in prices, which should therefore also respond to classical operators.
However, even before the introduction of such issues as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile on the market, voices similar to those we hear today were allowed to be heard in Great Britain.
However, it appears that he remained there for such operators and that they could have a real success.
We are not obliged to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you of the launch, in Poland, of the virtual mobileking operator.
In only six months, this operator has been able to win over 100 thousand customers and become the fifth operator of the country.
We add that behind the Mobilking there is the Penta financial group, which includes the U:fund in Czechia.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of focusing on a much more specific target group.
In order to be effective, they need much less customers than a classic operator.
They are, in fact, excluding costs of construction, operation and entertainment from the mobile network, relatively high.
So in the world, virtual operators are described as low-cost operators - they offer calls and good-market SMS, which is often counterbalanced by a limited provision of services.
