What method would be better to develop technologies that are capable of avoiding an obstacle if it is not the imitation of an existing barrier detector?
For example, one of the bees.
In the surprising project presented at CEATEC, which took place in Japan, the bourgeoisie gave the strategic idea of starting with Nissan engineers to inspire them in the way they should design the next generation of obstacles detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan built a small robot car, a bio-robotized control system of type BR23C, which has equipped the quality of bees, the ultimate goal is to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
In its flights, each bee is its own space, oval form, which, in fact, looks much like our secure protection coke - explained, at the exhibition Kazuhiro Doi, director of the research and development department and technological public relations of the brand.
The eye to facets of the bee plays a major role, since it is able to see in all directions, in a 300 degree angle.
In order to imitate the functions of the eye to facets, engineers approached the idea of the laser telemeter.
This identifies the obstacles in an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 metres before the BR23C, it assesses the distances and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which transforms it into a continuous avoidance.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a second fraction. Then, the mini robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it into an angle enough to avoid collision.
Unlike any existing system, this avoidance is carried out in an intensive manner.
"If it wasn't, the mini robot could not respond enough quickly to avoid the obstacle," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must act in an intensive and instantaneous way, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and internal layer of protection, a layer where collition is considered inevitable for the moment.
All this process must reflect on what the bee does to avoid other bees.
The process must take place in an eye-clin.
Unlike bees, the difference cannot go up, down or diagonally, it can be only two dimensions, and only in the direction in which the wheels can turn.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that possess the bees to avoid other bees, in our case, it was only possible to use rotational movement, acceleration and slowing down as manoeuvres available to the mini robot
The BR23C uses Lithium polymer batteries which are smaller and whose energy concentration is higher, making them longer lives than in the Lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is an instinctive intelligent reaction that is primary, not data processing, and even less storage capacity.
This mechanism must only deal with a few signs coming in second, and respond to them.
It is not necessary to store and react with intuitive logic based on the data of previous works. In this way, it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of continuous memory.
We don't need to remember a giant octets capacity or even mega octets.
This is the first step towards the design of a technology for immediate avoidance. According to Nissan's estimates, this system will enter the cars manufactured in series in the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system so that it can guide the driver to its destination by avoiding obstacles on its way.
