Industrial prices continued to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and by 12.9 per cent compared to August 2007 - the Central Statistics Office of Hungary reported.
Industrial export sales prices increased by 1.1 per cent compared with those of July 2008, while compared with those of the previous year, they decreased by 3.9 per cent.
As a result of internal and export fluctuations, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared to previous month and 3.2 per cent compared to previous year.
Internal industrial sales prices have only increased to a lesser extent: 0.1 per cent, compared with the previous month.
Internal sales prices in the transformation industry have increased only by 0.1 per cent compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather and leather manufacturing sector (2.8 per cent), with first place the manufacture of bags and centrifuges with a monthly increase of 4.6 per cent, then the production of shoes with 2.5 per cent monthly increase.
The higher price levels of primary plastic and chemical materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in prices in the manufacturing sector of chemicals (1.6 per cent).
A deflation has resulted in oil transformation sectors (1.4 per cent), the production of machinery and electrical equipment (0.9 per cent), as well as a minimum increase in wood processing (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing activities have not changed.
The other sectors of the transformation industry recorded an increase of 0.2 per cent and 0.9 per cent.
In the sectors of electricity, gas, steam and water supply, representing an important weight in national industrial operation, prices increased by 0.3 per cent in August, mainly due to the impact of the increase in gas prices established by the authorities since 1 July.
In a 12-month comparison, taking into account the internal sales of the transformation sectors, these are the prices of the oil processing sector which have seen the most significant increase (32.4 per cent).
In the manufacturing sector of metallurgy, prices increased by 13.2 per cent, while prices increased by 11 per cent in the important field of food, drink and tobacco production.
Price reductions took place in textile and textile production sectors (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machinery and equipment (0.3 per cent).
In other sectors of the transformation industry, prices rose between 0.6 per cent and 9.1 per cent.
In the entire transformation industry, prices increased by 10.2 per cent during the past year.
The prices of electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors exceeded 18.7 per cent of the previous year.
Among the intra-Community trade groups and according to sectoral competences, in August, these are the profit-producing sectors on investment which have shown a most significant monthly price rise (0.7 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, while the energy and materials sectors for further transformation were not known to change compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the most significant increase in energy and materials production sectors was observed for further transformation (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, inflation of 6.8 per cent was measured, while in the profit-producing sectors, a reduction of 1.4 per cent was measured.
The export sales prices of the industrial sector in HUF increased by 1.1 per cent in August compared to the previous month, while they fell by 3.9 per cent over 12 months.
In one month, our national payment average fell by 1.7 per cent compared to the euro, and 7.1 per cent to the dollar. Compared to August 2007, it increased by 7.5 per cent to the euro and 15.9 per cent to the dollar.
